    strategy:`<div class="stack"><div class="row"><div class="clamp" data-collapsed="true">
      <p><b>Act 1</b></p>
      <p>Goldor Blizzard III: Must be interrupted. If it goes off, it deals heavy damage and inflicts Deep Freeze, which will usually lead to a KO from the following Goldor Fire III.</p>
      <p>Goldor Fire III: A large AoE appears centered on you. After the first blast, three more AoEs appear in succession.</p>
      <p>Goldor Blast: A line AoE targeted at the player.</p>
      <p>Slimy Summon: Summons a Glittering Slime that is weak to ice damage but has high HP. If it is not defeated quickly, it will cast Rupture and kill the player.</p>
      <p>Goldor Quake: A circular AoE centered on Goldor, followed by two staggered donut AoEs.</p>
      <p>Goldor Fire: Summons 8 Ball of Fire adds that cast Burn. These are weak to wind damage. Defeat one first, then use the knockback to land in the safe area you created.</p>
      <p>Goldor Aero III: Used after Goldor Fire. Knocks the player back.</p>
      <p>Goldor Gravity: Inflicts Heavy for 12 seconds. This is followed by two casts of Goldor Blast.</p>
      <p>Goldor Thunder III: Summons random circle AoEs and inflicts Electrocution.</p>
      <p><b>Act 2</b></p>
      <p>Goldor reuses many mechanics from Act 1, but also begins fighting with his crystal.</p>
      <p>Shining Summon: Uses the crystal to summon gilded constructs. The early summons include Gilded Golems, Gilded Marionettes, and a Gilded Cyclops, each adding different overlapping mechanics that must be resolved in sequence.</p>
      <p>Gold Fever: Goldor becomes immune to magical damage and gains stronger magical attacks, while the Gilded Crystal becomes targetable. The crystal is also immune to magical damage, so physical damage is required.</p>
      <p>Later, Shining Summon returns with a large combined pattern, followed by repeated Goldor Blast casts. Correct positioning is required to survive the overlapping lane AoEs, cone AoEs, pulls, and blasts.</p>
      <p>Goldor Rush: Goldor combines Goldor Aero III, Goldor Thunder III, and Goldor Quake almost simultaneously, then quickly follows with three Goldor Blast casts. This covers much of the arena and forces either precise movement or a defensive survival strategy.</p>
      <p>After that, the rest of the act repeats the large-group Shining Summon, Goldor Gravity, Goldor Blizzard III, and Goldor Rush.</p>
    </div><div class="expand-wrap"><button class="expand-btn" data-role="expand"></button></div></div></div>`,

    tips:`<div class="stack"><div class="row"><div class="clamp" data-collapsed="true">
      <p>To earn All That Glitters Is Blue and the Gentlemage’s Umbrella weapon, complete the stage while casting all six elements, without using Sprint, and without destroying the crystal in Act 2.</p>
      <p>Because the crystal must remain intact, the rest of Act 2 has to be cleared with physical damage spells. Recommended options include Goblin Punch, Triple Trident, Both Ends, J Kick, Mountain Buster, Phantom Flurry, and Ruby Dynamics. The elemental requirement is easily completed during Act 1.</p>
      <p>Since Blue Mage’s strongest damage is usually magical, Act 2 becomes a long fight under these restrictions. Fortunately, the achievement has no time requirement and does not fail due to Vulnerability Up stacks.</p>
      <p>For a stable clear, use Aetheric Mimicry: Healer, heal with Pom Cure, recover MP with Lucid Dreaming between Goldor Rush sequences, and use the Mighty Guard + Diamondback method instead of trying to dodge Goldor Rush manually. Turn Mighty Guard off afterwards unless you are specifically continuing with Goblin Punch, which benefits from it.</p>
